1. Load Data¶

We wrote a specific ETL class to handle data loading and transformation. We only have to point to the csv location and optionally set the data types of the columns (which we do to reduce the data size a bit). We also convert the transit_timestamp column to a valid datetime format.

Disclaimer: During the task work it became apparent that each time period data obtained only starts at 13 o'clock instead of 1 o'clock, as during download the data was inappropiately filtered. During different attempts to obtain the missing hours as well via the website 500 errors where raised (in the csv file obtained), hence we could not adjust for this.

Before we dive into EDA let us quickly summarize how the data set is structured: One row corresponds to one hour at a specific day, for a specific station, and a specific fare class.

2. Exploratory Data Analysis¶

In the following we create a time period variable as for each of the target months (Mar 2022, Feb 2023 and Jan 2024) we obtained also the previous month.

In [10]:
cond_list = [df["year"] == 2022, 
            ((df["year"] == 2023) & (df["month"].isin([1, 2]))), # Select only Feb and Jan 2023
            ((df["year"] == 2023) & (df["month"] == 12)) | (df["year"] == 2024)] # Dec 2023 requires us to filter for specific year months
choice_list = ["Mar 22", "Feb 23", " Jan 24"] # labels for time periods
df["time_period"] = np.select(condlist=cond_list, choicelist=choice_list, default=np.nan)

Staten Island deviation is somewhat surprising, as the subway station is served 24/7. Otherwise, it is clear that the busiest days are usually business days, whereas weekends tend to be less busy. Before we verify this by generating ridership plots, let us further investigate why there are no daily_ridership zero values. We suspect that times, where either no one entered or left the station are simply omited from the data frame.

In [174]:
# We now calculate for each hour, how often an hour does not exist in the data set. We explicitly only look at subway stations, as the other two might have very different opening hours
df_test = df.copy()

# Only subway
mask = df_test["transit_mode"] == "subway"
df_test = df_test[mask]

# Aggregate to hours to remove influence of fare class
df_test = df_test.groupby(["station_complex_id", "date", "transit_timestamp"])["ridership"].agg("sum").reset_index()

# Step 1: Extract hour and date
df_test["date"] = df_test["transit_timestamp"].dt.date
df_test["hour"] = df_test["transit_timestamp"].dt.hour

# Step 2: Group by 'station_complex_id', 'date', and 'hour'
grouped = df_test.groupby(["station_complex_id", "date", "hour"]).size()

# Step 3: Create a full index of all expected hours for each station and date
dates = df_test["date"].unique()
hours = np.arange(24)  # 0 to 23 hours
stations = df_test["station_complex_id"].unique()

full_index = pd.MultiIndex.from_product([stations, dates, hours], names=["station_complex_id", "date", "hour"])

# Step 4: Reindex the grouped data to include all possible hours for each station and date
complete_data = grouped.reindex(full_index, fill_value=0)

# Step 5: Identify missing hours (where size is 0)
missing_hours = complete_data[complete_data == 0]

# Step 6: Count the number of times each specific hour is missing for each station
missing_counts = missing_hours.reset_index().groupby("hour").size()

We can certainly see that there seem to be hours where some stations are closed (1, 2, and 3 in the morning) but we can also see that there are missing hours across all possible hours, so we can safely assume that hours with no ridership lead to a missing row. To be fully save, let us retrieve some stations, with no ridership during the day, so we can be sure that those have nothing to do with opening hours.

We will later adjust the data to add rows in such cases with a ridership of zero. Now that this is sorted out, let us generate daily ridership plots to get a feel for the seasonality of the data.

In [11]:
# Prepare df and aggregate to borough and fare class per weekday
agg_df = df.groupby(["time_period", "borough", "fare_class_category", "weekday_name", "weekday"])["ridership"].sum().reset_index()

# Add total ridership
totals = agg_df.groupby(["time_period", "weekday_name", "fare_class_category", "weekday"])["ridership"].sum().reset_index()
totals["borough"] = "total"

# Concat
agg_df = pd.concat([agg_df, totals],ignore_index=True, axis=0)

# Order Weekday based on occurence in week
agg_df = agg_df.sort_values(["time_period", "borough", "fare_class_category", "weekday"])

# Create plot for each time period seperately
for tp in agg_df["time_period"].unique():
    mask = agg_df["time_period"] == tp
    subset_df = agg_df.loc[mask]
    fig = ts_lineplot_facet(subset_df, x_var="weekday_name", y_var="ridership", height=1100, width = 1200,
                      color="borough", title=f"Total ridership per Weekday, grouped by Borough for period {tp}",
                      facet_col="fare_class_category",facet_col_wrap=4)
    fig.for_each_annotation(lambda a: a.update(text=a.text.split("=")[-1])) # Remove var= in subtitle
    for axis in fig.layout:
        if axis.startswith('xaxis'):
            fig.layout[axis].showticklabels = True  # Ensuring tick labels are shown for all x-axes
            fig.layout[axis].title = None # Remove Variable title
    fig.show()

We can deduce the following:

  1. The expected pattern is clearly visable, where weekends are usually less busier than business days
  2. There are clearly changes in the distributions of ridership in fare classes across the timeperiods, although the ones with the highest ridership (OMNY / Metrocard - Full Fare) stay the same
  3. In period Mar 2022 there seem to be an unusal pattern where the maximum ridership is reached on Wednesday, in contrast in period Jan 2024 the peak is on Tuesday instead. In Feb 2023 the weekdays are fairly similar in their numbers, except Monday and Friday, which is the same for all periods.
  4. Unsurprisingly, Manhatten is the borough with the most riderships out of all of the six boroughs in the data set.
  5. It is kind of funny that students do not seem to use the public transport except for weekdays, which probably points to the fact that the students that do not live near their campus in dorms, have to travel a lot to get to campus.

Let us explicitly look at the different transit modes (i.e. subway, Staten Island Railway, and the Roosevelt Island Tram) as we would expect a difference in ridership volumes)

In a sense our assumption was partly correct, as we can clearly see peaks or a local maximums around Saturday and Sunday for the Roosevalt Island tram. After research we can also understand why Staten Island does still exhibit the same pattern as the rest of the boroughs. Staten Island is actually an area that includes residential as well as commercial buildings, hence the the Staten Island Railway is probably used for commuting to work or to get home, and not mainly to visit tourist attractions.

Let us now also look at the full time periods, maybe we can detect some outliers in the seasonal pattern.

We make the following observations:

  1. The daily ridership range seems to be different in Mar 22 when compared to the other two periods.
  2. We can clearly detect two outlier weeks, one is Christmas in 2023 and the other one is the week starting from 31st of January in 2022. Looking at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/February_2022_North_American_winter_storm yields that New York City was impacted by a significant winter storm, which explains the outlier.
  3. Lastly, the ridership figures for the beginning of December seem to be higher than the rest of the time periods, which might be explained by a higher tourist account or in general that people travel a lot more to get to attractions / buy presents.

2.3 Stations which exhibit unusal patterns¶

Before we move on, let us quickly try to foreshadow whether some stations are much harder to predict. We suspect that stations whose ridership numbers fluctuate a lot during business days or stations where the general seasonality is reversed (i.e. having a higher ridership on weekends than on business days) are more difficult to predict. The first because of the high variance and the seemingly unimportance of the seasonal effect that is going to work and the second due to being most likely stations near tourist attractions or leisure venues which in turn means that the causal factors driving ridership are potentially different from those stations where the seasonal effect is the main mechanism.

For the first we look at the interquartile range of relative ridership per day to the total ridership for that station per week. This is done, to account for the different order of magnitude in ridership numbers between stations. For the second we will look at the quantiles of the distribution of the relative ridership on business days compared to weekends.

3. Forecasting¶

This section is organized as follows. First, we will sample two stations each from the quartiles, transform the time series data for forecasting, and have a small visual analysis using ACF and PACF plots to determine stationarity and seasonality patterns explicitly. In the next section we are then going to train and evaluate two models, an ARIMA model and a LightGBM based boosted decision tree regressor. We will also explain our rationale behind choosing those models, as well as the training process. Finally, we will also provide forecasts for the stations we suspected difficult to predict and evaluate the effect of adding an additional feature to the ensemble model.

3.1 Data Preperation and Station Selection¶

As before, the main code is contained in the DataLoader class, available from the etl.py module. Here we already provide transformations that allow one to do the following:

  1. Given a list of station ids, a start and end date, subset the data frame attribute accordingly. Here we also allow one to specifiy additional variables that should be retained and how they should be aggregated in the process.
  2. For each station id and day:hour aggregate (sum) the ridership variable (thus ignoring fare class differences) and potentially additional variables.
  3. As hours with no ridership are non-existing, the function will (depending upon user request) add the missing hours with a ridership of zero and potentially impute NAs in additional variables*
  4. Finally, based on user input a column is added that indicates train and test set observations (in our case the first two weeks of the respective time periods)

As training horizon we opted for one month because on one hand this includes the previous month weeks of the test set and because we are sceptical whether a longer training window would benefit any model, as the the forecast is on hourly basis. Besides, we favor in this presentation execution time over model performance.

Note: The data we downloaded starts always at 13 o'clock on the first day of the previous month. We tried to query the data again to get the other hours as well, but only got partial data due to a 500 error. This will not lead to wrongly added zero ridership values, as the code only consideres missing hours between the start and end time index.

*The first non-null value of that variable of the given day would then be used.

Let us quickly verify our seasonal finding by also plotting the power spectral density using a periodogram (again only for the March 22 period). A periodogram uses Fourier transformation to estimate the spectral density of a signal. One could think of a decomposition of any signal (time series) into many different sinus functions and at each period (in our case, generally frequency is used) the amplitude of all of the sinus function is aggregated and squared to produce the so called Power of the period, i.e. the influence on the signal. In our implementation we can use this to identify seasonal components by looking at the period of power peaks.

3.2 Model Training & Forecasting¶

Before we proceed let us summarize our approach for the following two sections and provide our rationale. First of all, we opted for an ARIMA model as a "simple" base line model and compare it to a non-linear machine learning model (i.e. the ensemble model). As ARIMA models are easy to understand, explainable, and widely used, we propose that any other model selected, should at least outperform this base line model (assuming prediction performance is the key metric). We decided to use the LightGBM implementation both because it is faster than XGBoost, but also because boosted tree regressors tend to produce solid results in time series regression tasks (see e.g. the M5 competition https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0169207021001874). In the last chapter we also highlight other models we did not try, but would have liked to do so.

For the error metric we opted for the mean absolute scaled error (MASE) with the modification for seasonal time series. The rationale behind this is twofold. One is the inapplicability of other available metrics given our goal (staffing of stations) and the underlying data. We see huge differences in total ridership between stations, not only daily but also hourly and any metric prone to absolute scales such as MAE or MSE wouldn't allow us to compare error metrics between series (stations). Additionally, as the ranges in absolute terms are quite large for some stations, we would probably over- or understaff stations with high absolute ridership numbers. Percentage based error metrics are also off the table, as there are hours with 0 ridership and thus they would need to be crudely adjusted. Scaled error metrics such as MASE are not prone to these shortcomings, but in the case of MASE have one drawback: One has to define a seasonal window for the naive forecaster used. In our case, we can be certain that 24 is a seasonal cycle (see 3.1) but from 2.2 we also suspect that there is a seasonal weekly cycle and the periodograms also showed many short term seasonality effects. In a real-world scenario we would have created a custom error metric, which combines both seasonal components we know of (and potentially even more) into one metric using weights to obtain a more nuanced metric.

MASE (seasonal) formula from Wikipedia:

Here $e_j$ is the absolute forecast error, which is then compared with the error a naive forecaster would incurr. $m$ describes the seasonal shift, so in our case $m=24$

Finally, the method used to produce the forecasts will always be recursive, meaning each hour is predicted one at the time, possibly including data previously forecasted. This not only has computational reasons but we suspected that the validation window is quite large, given our training size, so direct methods wouldn't be trained that well.

3.2.1 ARIMA¶

We will extensively utilize the sktime library, as well as the LightGBM library to train the models. We opted for the LightGBM implementation, as it is usually much faster than XGBoost, again suiting our perspective within this task that faster computation is more important than performance. Again, note that the ARIMA implementation in sktime is a wrapper around pmdarima which is an AutoARIMA implementation for Python. As the ARIMA model is not readily capable of providing predictions for multiple time series, multiple models (one each each station / period combination) are fitted under the hood in sktime. Let us for simplicity first fit a single ARIMA model to the first station in the first period and have a look at its performance.

After reviewing the model summaries (not depicted here for visual reasons) for all station at this period, we can see that the models selected usually differ from the parameters we picked, except in one case. Most of the time the differences are not to large, except for the AR components, where most models do not include any lag. But after plotting one exemplary model (see below) we can also understand why. The forecast is most of the time a constant as the ARIMA model is ill-suited to handle the seasonality patterns. Because of this, we modify the model call a bit to fit a SARIMA model instead, which includes specific AR and MA components for each seasonal component. As we already identified one clear peak at the 24 hour mark, we will use this as seasonality differencing parameter.

We will now plot the results for the full March period, but omit the other periods and only calculate the error values instead.

3.2.2 Boosted Tree Regressor (LightGBM)¶

We are going to train the boosted tree regressor using the sktime library as well. Under the hood, the data is first transformed such that lags are added as new columns. The model is going to be trained using cross-validation and grid search for the lags hyperparameter, i.e. what lag window to choose (a lag window of 2 means t-1 and t-2 lags). For the cross-validation an expanding window is used, where we start with roughly 70% of the first occuring train data as train set and evaluate the model on the rest of the train set. This window is expanded to the right at every iteration. We choose an expanding window over a moving one as in a deployment scenario we would likely select a model that can learn better from additional samples. The search grid was designed based on the periodograms, where we offer more granular values for the lags up to 12 hours and less granular choices but definetly including 24 hours up to 48 hours.

Unfortunatly it was not possible for us to construct one model for each time period instead of again multiple models based on the station id, as we got error messages that were not documented anywhere, even after following the suggested steps. Ideally one would fit one model for one or multiple stations over all periods, but as we have three different, consecutive validation periods this makes it quite difficult to use temporal cross-validation effectively. We will give a more extensive comment in the last section when we discuss deployment and improvement of the model.

Here we produce plots for every time period as this would be considered our main model candidate. Important Note: Unfortunately it is currently not possible to get in-sample, i.e. training set predictions for the sktime object that is used for training the LightGBM model, as it is not implemented by the sktime team yet. We could not find a method to access the trained LightGBM object to produce the values manually. This came only apparent very late in development, hence we could not switch to a different package or implement the sktime utilities ourselves. The values in the plots will correspond only to the training set each.

3.3 Further Developments that couldn't be implemented due to time constraints¶

As available development time was limited, we could not implement everything we would have liked to do. Nevertheless, we still want to highlight what we've tried next.

  1. Further improve the GBM model through feature engineering. In particular add proximity to next holiday within 3 week window and running means of target variable, weekday (categoricals can be handled by LightGBM well);
  2. Try Facebooks Prophet model, as it well suited to address time series with seasonal patterns and compare with GBM and SARIMA;
  3. Addinbg more hyperparameters to GBM hyperparameter tuning, for example learning rate or max depth of decision stumps;
  4. Clustering of stations and development of models for each cluster instead of per station and time period.

Finally, I personally like to implement evaluation scripts / classes to better understand where errors estimators make are coming from, e.g. whether weekends are more prone to errors than business days etc.

Other additions would require external data, which we will also discuss in the next and last section.

4. Additional Tasks¶

4.1 Deployment Concept¶

Before we can think about deployment, we should first identify a key business metric or some business releated quantitative goal we want to reach to ensure that not only a performant model is deployed but also one that delivers value beyond predictive accuracy. One example could in this context be to gather rider feedback for stations or station service. This could then be combined with the expenditures per day / hour that occur from personal to give a metric that accounts for costs, as well as customer satisfaction. Either an upfront quasi-experimental A/B test would deliver a go for deployment or the metric could be used to track continuous improvement of the deployed model.

Additionally, it makes sense before deployment to think about satisficing metrics, e.g. execution time or cloud ressources budgets that the deployment model should satisfy. If deployment has been decided we identify the following key areas that would need to be adressed: ETL, Feature Engineering, Model Training & Logging, Inference, Monitoring.

ETL:

  • A script would need to be created that uses classes / methods defined as for example in the etl.py module to gather or load the MTA as well as any other data, combines them, performs appropiate transformations and quality checks. This could then be scheduled as a data ingestion pipeline.

Feature Engineering:

  • Similar to the ETL area, we would need to define a script that uses the prepared data to construct meaningful features or performs final preparations to the data set, such as train / test splits.
  • Add a script that would ingest sample weights to the final data or add a feature that captures external influences on ridership (outages, construction work) to be able to steer retraining better (e.g. in case of recent outages, the data would not be representative)

Model Training & Logging:

  • A general framework for defining models (from a programmatic perspective) would be required, e.g. by agreeing on base class methods any model should have. This can then be used to set requirements for new model candidates (again from a programmatic perspective)
  • Generate model specific module (if required) and a generic train script returning the GBM model object adjusted to fulfill the class framework requirements
  • A script that is wrapper around model definition / train scripts, which ideally uses a model versioning framework, e.g. Mlflow or Sagemaker, to save a model and its predictions (train/validation/test) and includes functionalities for model comparison with the registered production model, while additionally logging results of training and validation, as well as CPU / Memory performance related metrics.

Inference:

  • A script that performs the actual deployment of the logged model to a dedicated endpoint, which can either be accessed via private network or via a public ip
  • A module that contains functions to interact with the deployment model, in particular requesting a forecast given some input data (should be available ETL & Feature Engineering Step) and that saves it response where needed

Monitoring:

  • A script that can periodically be run that uses the current production model and requests forecasts for periods which have already occured, but where not included in the train set of the deployed model. The resulting error metrics should be logged and potentially automatic alarms are set in the cloud environment if certain metrics are too low. This script should also take into account the business metric defined.

I would initially opt to retrain every month due to the forecast horizon or earlier depending on an alert from monitoring.

Scaling To be able to scale to all stations, the script would need to be adjusted to be able to create models for two groupings, in particular I would perform clustering on the stations and fit models on those clusters to reduce the total number of models.

4.2 External Data¶

We would opt to add the following data sources, which are mostly available publicly via an API (and could hence be incorporated in the ETL step mentioned in 4.1). Depending on ressources and nature of the data (i.e. size, availability) it might be beneficial to create seperate ETL pipelines for some sources.

  • Opening & Closing times of stations: The subway itself runs 24/7 but there are construction works, the Roosevelt Stations that have opening hours (depending on holidays even). This is either scrapable from the Web or, since we are MTA available internally. Adding those would allow us to discard wrongfully ridership of zero rows from the data or provide the model with information why pattern for other stations change;
  • Weather data: Weather can hugely influence ridership volumes (see February storm 2022) and hence past, current, and forecasted weather date can prove useful to improve the model;
  • Tourist data: Especially the number of tourists (probably published by NYC) for each month / week, if possible by borough. Additionally number of visitors for tourist attractions (to be able to identify stations where many riders are tourists)
  • Event data: Data on sports events or concerts / shows, especially date and venue to be able to locate nearest stations
  • Price data: If not quite stable, data on the prices of fares could prove useful, especially in anticipating trend changes.

4.3 Continuous Model Improvement¶

As already mentioned, one possible idea would be to regularly conduct surveys regarding rider satisfaction of stations, so that quasi-experimental A/B experiments could be run for the current production model and a new candidate model that does not only take into account predictive power but also business value added. Here it would make sense to define a general list of acceptance criterias in terms of metrics (business & model) and other criterias, like model execution time. The reason is, that at some point it takes most likely a huge amount of time & money to improve the metrics further which in turn would hurt the business value added.

Depending whether a concrete experimental setup is meant, incl. treatment effect estimation / model ranking, this is probably something that can easier be discussed in the interview.

As discussed, we now retrain the GBM model with the same parameters as before but now use the 15 station we selected in 2.3 and train the models for the March 22 period. Afterwards, we compare the error metrics obtained with the error values for the March 22 period using the quartile stations.
